***************  Locator CSS   ************

.getattribute() ----> value of the attribute

________________________________________________
 CSS

 1.get an Element using CSS selector
  Syntax:
        tagname[attribute='attribute value']
     f.e. a[data-testid='open-registration-form-button']

  The beauty about CSS selector is that instead of writing the full
  sybtax u can also use shortcuts

  classname-----> tagname[classname='value'] u can write "tagname.value"----> .
  ID     -------> tagname[id='value'] u can write    "tagname#value"--->#

  In css selector we don't have the option of getting an element by TEXT

  Css has contains method that can be used
  Syntax:
            tagname[attribute*='partial attribute value']
  Css has some other amazing features to like
     a. starts-with method in css;
            tagname[attribute^='starting attribute value']   where ^ means starts with

    b.  ends with method in css
             tagname[attribute$='ending attribute value']  where $ means end value

    ---------------------------------------------------
Radio Buttons


.isEnabled()---> if we can select the button(greyed out(not selectable)) boolean
.isSelected()----->check if button is selected  boolean
.isDisplayed()---->visible or not     boolen

Radio Button and Checkboxes are almost the same


Approach to single checkbox:
1.inspect the checkbox
2.write down the correct locator in the Dom
3.use find Element to find the checkbox
4.click on it

if I want to check that check box is selected?
checkbox.isSelected()---> True (means selected)

Approach to multiple checkboxes:
1.inspect in the DOM
2.writethe locator in such a way that it is able to select all the required checkbox
3. use find ElementS to get all those checkbox
4. iterate through the list
5. while iteration look for your desires checkbox
if condition to make the selection





